<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Atriplex canescens </i>is a widespread shrub in the western United States. It is extremely variable in physiology, form, and other characteristics. Plants are long-lived and resistant to salt, cold, and drought; they tolerate saline, alkaline, boron, and gypsum soils, but they are not an indicator of these conditions (Howard 2003). The species has been used extensively for rehabilitation of mine excavations in Montana and Wyoming. It colonizes readily from seed and does not appear to require mycorrhizal associations to grow vigorously. It tolerates grazing. <br/>
<br/>
<i>A. canescens </i>is the most rapidly evolving shrub in North America; plants have different polyploidy levels, and the species contains regional ecotypes (Howard 2003). Moreover, identification is challenging due to intraspecific variation and introgression with other saltbush species. It grows extensively in California, but the alliance is largely restricted to the deserts, the San Joaquin Valley, and surrounding foothills. Two of the six subspecies of <i>A. canescens </i>(ssp. <i>canescens </i>and ssp. <i>linearis</i>) grow in California. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
