    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Ai-k). Local stands cover low hills and edges of valleys in the inland sections. Its robust plants may represent a different ecotype from those in the deserts.</li>
        
            <li><b>Colorado Desert</b> (322Ca-d). Stands occur in similar situations as the Mojave Desert, including playa edges at Clark Dry Lake in Earthquake Valley and alkaline springs in Anza-Borrego Desert State Park (Keeler- Wolf et al. 1998b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Av, Ay-z). Stands occur scattered in alkaline areas within the San Joaquin Valley.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Aa-p). Stands exist throughout the section (Thomas et al. 2004), such as on dune aprons and low dunes in Death and Saline valleys, and on moderately alkaline playas at Silver Dry and Superior Dry lakes. Stands occur less commonly and are smaller than those of the <i>Atriplex polycarpa</i> alliance. Stands are more restricted to alkaline areas and do not occur on rocky uplands. They often mix with stands of the <i>Prosopis glandulosa</i> alliance along streams and washes or at the edges of dunes, and they commonly associate with <i>Suaeda moquinii</i> stands at playa edges.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northwestern Basin and Range</b> (342Ba, Bc, Be). Stands exist around the alkali lakes, such as in Surprise Valley in Modoc Co.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sonoran Desert</b> (322Ba, Bc-e). Stands are local around playa edges, adjacent to springs, and with <i>Prosopis glandulosa</i> and <i>Suaeda moquinii</i> stands along the Colorado River and in the Chuckwalla and Cadiz-Vidal valleys (Evens and Hartman 2007).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fc, Ff). Stands occupy edges of playas and valleys and flats with clay soil in the northern Panamint Range. Stand elevations are higher in this section, suggesting a different ecotype than in hot deserts.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bi-l). Small, as yet unsampled stands occur in western Riverside Co.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> In general, this alliance is in relatively good standing throughout its range. Its ability to tolerate alkaline soils, grazing, fire, and other disturbance bodes well for its persistence. High levels of grazing and fire at certain times of the year may be detrimental (Howard 2003), especially in cismontane stands. </div>
</div>

    

    

